TY  - JOUR
AU  - Mankiw, N. Gregory
AU  - Rotemberg, Julio J.
AU  - Summers, Lawrence H.
T1  - Intertemporal Substitution in Macroeconomics*
PY  - 1985
Y1  - 1985/02/01
DO  - 10.2307/1885743
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 100
IS  - 1
SP  - 225
EP  - 251
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Modern neoclassical business cycle theories posit that the observed fluctuations in consumption and employment correspond to decisions of an optimizing representative individual. We estimate three first-order conditions that represent three tradeoffs faced by such an optimizing individual. He can trade off present for future consumption, present for future leisure, and present consumption for present leisure. The aggregate U. S. data lend no support to this model. The overidentifying restrictions are rejected, and the estimated utility function is often convex. Even when it is concave, the estimates imply that either consumption or leisure is an inferior good.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1885743
ER  - 



