PY  - 1985
Y1  - 1985/02/01
DO  - 10.2307/1885734
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 100
IS  - 1
SP  - 29
EP  - 56
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This paper tests for the existence of wage premiums based on geographic and industry unemployment differences. These differences are broken down into permanent and transitory components in equations controlling for variation in state generosity of unemployment insurance benefits. Findings indicate that wage premiums arise for long-run unemployment differences, but that negative short-run shocks to industries generate wage cuts, while positive shocks generate wage hikes. Therefore, labor contracts accommodate long-term anticipated unemployment, and entail sharing of short-term unemployment risks.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1885734
ER  - 



